Here's the full picture:

## Where `skill_mcp` is defined

**`oh-my-opencode` plugin** — [`src/tools/skill-mcp/tools.ts`](https://github.com/code-yeongyu/oh-my-opencode/blob/dev/src/tools/skill-mcp/tools.ts)

It's registered in the tool registry at [`src/plugin/tool-registry.ts`](https://github.com/code-yeongyu/oh-my-opencode/blob/dev/src/plugin/tool-registry.ts):
```ts
skill_mcp: skillMcpTool,
```

## How it works (the exact failure path)

The key function is `findMcpServer`:

```ts
function findMcpServer(mcpName, skills) {
  for (const skill of skills) {
    if (skill.mcpConfig && mcpName in skill.mcpConfig) {  // ← your skill has no mcpConfig
      return { skill, config: skill.mcpConfig[mcpName] }
    }
  }
  return null  // ← returns null → throws "MCP server not found"
}
```

It iterates loaded skills looking for one that has `mcpConfig` with a matching key. Your `parallel-search` skill has **no `mcpConfig`** because the skill loader (`async-loader.ts`) populates it from either:

1. **`mcp.json`** file in the skill directory (with a `mcpServers` block)
2. **SKILL.md frontmatter** with `mcpServers` field

Your skill has neither — just `name` and `description` in the frontmatter. So `skill.mcpConfig` is `undefined`, and the tool throws.

## What your skill needs

An **`mcp.json`** file alongside `SKILL.md`:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "parallel-search": {
      "url": "https://search-mcp.parallel.ai/mcp"
    }
  }
}
```

Or equivalently, add `mcpServers` to the SKILL.md frontmatter. That's what connects the `skill_mcp` bridge to the actual remote MCP endpoint.

